title: Nuclear reactions induced by alpha particles on natural ytterbium

x4freetext: Nuclear reactions induced by alpha particles on
natural ytterbium

x4codes.hlp: Comision Nacional de Energia Atomica, Buenos Aires, Argentina

x4freetext: Comision Nacional de Energia Atomica,
Buenos Aires
Natural ytterbium foils,
purity: 99.9%, thickness: 15.83 mg/cm**2;
wrapped in aluminum, thickness: 3.72 mg/cm**2.
Incident energy of the alpha beam: 84.32 MeV,
intensity: 3.2 microA.
The beam current was determined using monitor
excitation functions.
The irradiation lasted 240 minutes.
Photopeak areas were obtained by adjusting the peak
distribution with a gaussian shape plus a straight
background.
The detector was calibrated in energy and efficiency
using a set of radioactive sources with well-known
activities: 22Na, 57Co, 60Co, 133Ba, 137Cs, 152Eu.
Cu foils, thickness: 26.85 mg/cm**2;
Al wrapping, thickness: 3.72 mg/cm**2.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.131, p.513 (1969)

x4freetext: The calculations and the energy distribution in the
stack were made using the code STP.
The uncertainties in the cross sections arise
essentially from the errors in the peak areas and the
efficiency calibration.
The contribution of the first factor
depends on the peak area and the background, and was
estimated to be around 5% to 8%.
The second contributes with 5%.
Therefore, the data are affected by an overall error
The experimental data were compared with the
independently interacting excitons, the Index model,
which can explain both the equilibrium and
pre-equilibrium effects.
